<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-035-338 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 407 623</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 14 1991 v8 n41 p16(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Symantec's Time Line update sports new control features. (TimeLine 5.0) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ferranti, Marc.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Symantec Corp announces Time Line 5.0, a major upgrade to thecompany's popular project-management software package thatincludes new resource control and modeling features.andP;  It offersIndividual Resource Calendars, which improve the accuracy ofscheduling by letting users account for interruptions such asvacations, and a Task Splitting feature that can be used with theresource calendars to assign work on specific tasks.andP;  ResourceContouring is a feature that automatically assigns partiallyavailable resources to a task.andP;  These new high-end capabilitiesmake Time Line competitive with more expensive programs.andP;  TimeLine 5.0 sells for $699 for a single-user version and $599 pernode for a LAN version.andP;  Upgrades are priced at $129 and $99respectively until Dec 15, 1991.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Symantec Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    SYMC.andO;Product:   Time Line 5.0 (Project management software) (Productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Project management systemsSoftware packagesProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Marc FerrantiandM;Advanced resource-management features and multiple-project capabilities topthe list of new features in Time Line 5.0, an upgrade to Symantec Corp.'spopular project-management program.andM;Time Line 5.0, due this week, is the first upgrade in more than a year andhalf, and it is designed to allow users to build more accurate models ofprojects, according to Chris Kocher, vice president of Symantec'sproject-management group in Novato, Calif.andP;  This helps managers optimizeschedules and meet deadlines and budgets, he said.andM;Individual Resource Calendars, for example, improve accuracy of scheduling byallowing users to account for interruptions such as vacations, Kocher said.andO;The Task Splitting feature can be used together with the resource calendarsto assign work on a specific task, have it interrupted, then resume after avacation or other suspension of work.andM;Greater control over schedules is available through a feature called ResourceContouring.andP;  This capability automatically assigns partially availableresources to a task, rather than forcing managers to wait until all resourcesare at hand before work on a task can begin.andP;  Tasks assigned higherpriorities are first to use spare resources.andM;Beta testers also cited the ability to set varying levels of efficiency forcertain resources -- when, for example, new employees work more slowly thanexperienced ones -- and varying cost rates.andM;&quot;The new resource capabilities are just as important for accounting as theyare for scheduling,&quot; said beta tester Bill Woloch, project manager atSverdrup Corp., a design and construction company in Falls Church, Va.andP;  Thevarying cost rates let managers take salary raises into account, while theindividual resource calendars are especially important for companies thathire part-time help, he said.andM;High-End CapabilitiesandM;Woloch also said that the new multiproject capabilities bring to Time Linecapabilities usually associated with more expensive programs.andP;  Time Line 5.0can, for example, do resource leveling (allocation of resources) acrossmultiple projects, which is important in companies where many projects sharea pool of resources.andP;  Time Line can also link to subprojects created in OnTarget, Symantec's entry-level project manager.andM;Time Line is priced at $699 for a stand-alone unit and $599 for simultaneoususe on a LAN node.andM;Upgrades until Dec.andP;  15 are priced at $129 for stand-alone and $99 for LANusers; upgrade pricing after Dec.andP;  15 is $179 and $149, respectively.andO;</TEXT></DOC>